00:05:46.530 --> 00:05:50.550
how we've used this framework
to give users the tool

00:05:50.550 --> 00:05:53.705
to engage in the ideation
and creation process.

00:05:56.340 --> 00:05:59.440
And now that you understand
the structure of a sprint,

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:01.770
when's the right time to sprint?

00:06:01.770 --> 00:06:04.620
Really, you can sprint at
any point in the lifecycle

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:05.940
of your product.

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:07.770
You might be at
the very beginning

00:06:07.770 --> 00:06:10.770
and want to use the sprint
for visioning or creating

00:06:10.770 --> 00:06:11.880
a roadmap.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:13.590
You may have a mature
product, and you're

00:06:13.590 --> 00:06:16.530
thinking about adding
a specific feature.

00:06:16.530 --> 00:06:18.930
Whatever point in the
life cycle of your product

00:06:18.930 --> 00:06:21.180
that you run a sprint,
it's important to remember

00:06:21.180 --> 00:06:24.360
that involving users
early and often

00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:26.520
can really help validate
the problem space

00:06:26.520 --> 00:06:27.750
and create better ideas.

00:06:30.669 --> 00:06:32.710
